Tidy a(n) gmm object

Source: R/gmm-tidiers.R
tidy.gmm.Rd

Tidy summarizes information about the components of a model. A model component might be a single term in a regression, a single hypothesis, a cluster, or a class. Exactly what tidy considers to be a model component varies across models but is usually self-evident. If a model has several distinct types of components, you will need to specify which components to return.

# S3 method for gmm
tidy(x, conf.int = FALSE, conf.level = 0.95, exponentiate = FALSE, ...)

Arguments

x

A gmm object returned from gmm::gmm().
conf.int

Logical indicating whether or not to include a confidence interval in the tidied output. Defaults to FALSE.
conf.level

The confidence level to use for the confidence interval if conf.int = TRUE. Must be strictly greater than 0 and less than 1. Defaults to 0.95, which corresponds to a 95 percent confidence interval.
exponentiate

Logical indicating whether or not to exponentiate the the coefficient estimates. This is typical for logistic and multinomial regressions, but a bad idea if there is no log or logit link. Defaults to FALSE.
...

Additional arguments. Not used. Needed to match generic signature only. Cautionary note: Misspelled arguments will be absorbed in ..., where they will be ignored. If the misspelled argument has a default value, the default value will be used. For example, if you pass conf.lvel = 0.9, all computation will proceed using conf.level = 0.95. Additionally, if you pass newdata = my_tibble to an augment() method that does not accept a newdata argument, it will use the default value for the data argument.

See also

tidy(), gmm::gmm()

Other gmm tidiers: glance.gmm()

Value

A tibble::tibble() with columns:

conf.high

Upper bound on the confidence interval for the estimate.

conf.low

Lower bound on the confidence interval for the estimate.

estimate

The estimated value of the regression term.

p.value

The two-sided p-value associated with the observed statistic.

statistic

The value of a T-statistic to use in a hypothesis that the regression term is non-zero.

std.error

The standard error of the regression term.

term

The name of the regression term.

# examples come from the "gmm" package
## CAPM test with GMM
data(Finance)
#> Warning: data set ‘Finance’ not found
r <- Finance[1:300, 1:10]
#> Error in eval(expr, envir, enclos): object 'Finance' not found
rm <- Finance[1:300, "rm"]
#> Error in eval(expr, envir, enclos): object 'Finance' not found
rf <- Finance[1:300, "rf"]
#> Error in eval(expr, envir, enclos): object 'Finance' not found

z <- as.matrix(r - rf)
#> Error in as.matrix(r - rf): object 'r' not found
t <- nrow(z)
#> Error in nrow(z): object 'z' not found
zm <- rm - rf
#> Error in rm - rf: non-numeric argument to binary operator
h <- matrix(zm, t, 1)
#> Error in matrix(zm, t, 1): object 'zm' not found
res <- gmm(z ~ zm, x = h)
#> Error in gmm(z ~ zm, x = h): could not find function "gmm"

# tidy result
tidy(res)
#> Error in tidy(res): object 'res' not found
tidy(res, conf.int = TRUE)
#> Error in tidy(res, conf.int = TRUE): object 'res' not found
tidy(res, conf.int = TRUE, conf.level = .99)
#> Error in tidy(res, conf.int = TRUE, conf.level = 0.99): object 'res' not found

# coefficient plot
library(ggplot2)
library(dplyr)

tidy(res, conf.int = TRUE) %>%
  mutate(variable = reorder(term, estimate)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(estimate, variable)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_errorbarh(aes(xmin = conf.low, xmax = conf.high)) +
  geom_vline(xintercept = 0, color = "red", lty = 2)
#> Error in tidy(res, conf.int = TRUE): object 'res' not found

# from a function instead of a matrix
g <- function(theta, x) {
  e <- x[, 2:11] - theta[1] - (x[, 1] - theta[1]) %*% matrix(theta[2:11], 1, 10)
  gmat <- cbind(e, e * c(x[, 1]))
  return(gmat)
}

x <- as.matrix(cbind(rm, r))
#> Error in cbind(rm, r): object 'r' not found
res_black <- gmm(g, x = x, t0 = rep(0, 11))
#> Error in gmm(g, x = x, t0 = rep(0, 11)): could not find function "gmm"

tidy(res_black)
#> Error in tidy(res_black): object 'res_black' not found
tidy(res_black, conf.int = TRUE)
#> Error in tidy(res_black, conf.int = TRUE): object 'res_black' not found

## APT test with Fama-French factors and GMM

f1 <- zm
#> Error in eval(expr, envir, enclos): object 'zm' not found
f2 <- Finance[1:300, "hml"] - rf
#> Error in eval(expr, envir, enclos): object 'Finance' not found
f3 <- Finance[1:300, "smb"] - rf
#> Error in eval(expr, envir, enclos): object 'Finance' not found
h <- cbind(f1, f2, f3)
#> Error in cbind(f1, f2, f3): object 'f1' not found
res2 <- gmm(z ~ f1 + f2 + f3, x = h)
#> Error in gmm(z ~ f1 + f2 + f3, x = h): could not find function "gmm"

td2 <- tidy(res2, conf.int = TRUE)
#> Error in tidy(res2, conf.int = TRUE): object 'res2' not found
td2
#> Error in eval(expr, envir, enclos): object 'td2' not found

# coefficient plot
td2 %>%
  mutate(variable = reorder(term, estimate)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(estimate, variable)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_errorbarh(aes(xmin = conf.low, xmax = conf.high)) +
  geom_vline(xintercept = 0, color = "red", lty = 2)
#> Error in eval(lhs, parent, parent): object 'td2' not found
